Load libraries

These are the libraries Ill be using in this tutorial.

library(tidyverse)
library(sf)
library(leaflet)
library(htmltools)
library(htmlwidgets)
library(raster)
library(gstat)
library(spatial)

Dataset

Cambridge maintains neighborhood level data on COVID case rates (the number of cases per 10,000 residents), which you can view here (click on Neighborhood Map on the left sidebar).

Visualizing differences among neighborhoods.

I can create my own version of the Cambridge COVID neighborhood map. Ill start by downloading neighborhood boundaries from the citys open data portal and displaying those boundaries on a leaflet map.

cambridge_nhoods <- st_read("https://data.cambridgema.gov/api/geospatial/4ys2-ebga?method=export&format=GeoJSON", quiet = TRUE) %>%
  dplyr::select(name)

leaflet(cambridge_nhoods) %>%
  addProviderTiles(providers$Stamen.TonerLite) %>%
  addPolygons(highlightOptions = highlightOptions(fillColor = "yellow", 
                                                  fillOpacity = 1),
              label = ~name, 
              weight = 1)

Now Ill manually add the case rates from that map (this is the most tedious, error-prone approach possible to loading the data, but Ive been unable to find the data for download, and its only 13 points, so its fine).

Then, Ill add labels and colors to the map to indicate the case rate in each neighborhood.

cambridge_nhoods <- cambridge_nhoods %>%
  mutate(case_rate = c(166, 66, 91, 25, 99, 72, 144, 
                       164, 45, 90, 11, 73, 114))

cambridge_nhoods$label <- 
  paste(cambridge_nhoods$name, "<br>", 
        cambridge_nhoods$case_rate, " cases per 10,000 residents") %>% 
  lapply(htmltools::HTML)

bins <- seq(min(cambridge_nhoods$case_rate),
            max(cambridge_nhoods$case_rate), by = 1)
pal <- colorNumeric("viridis", 
                    domain = cambridge_nhoods$case_rate,
                    na.color = "#00000000")

leaflet(cambridge_nhoods) %>%
  addProviderTiles(providers$Stamen.TonerLite) %>%
  addPolygons(highlightOptions = highlightOptions(fillOpacity = 1),
              label = ~label,
              fillColor = ~pal(case_rate),
              weight = 1, color = "black") %>% 
  addLegend(pal = pal, 
            values = ~case_rate,
            bins = 3,
            opacity = 0.7, title = "Cases per 10,000 residents",
            position = "topright")

From this map, it appears that there are sudden changes in COVID risk at neighborhood boundaries. For example, it might appear that when you cross Mass Ave to go from The Port to Cambridgeport, the COVID risk decreases from 166 in 100,0000 to 99 in 100,000. In reality, COVID risk probably varies more smoothly.

Neighborhood-level rates as points

Lets assume that the average COVID rate for a neighborhood is most likely to representative of the very middle of the neighborhood (the centroid), but that as you move closer to the edges of the neighborhood, it starts to look more like the adjacent neighborhoods.

If thats more or less whats happening, if might make sense to represent the COVID case rates as points rather than polygons. Note that to calculate centroids, Im transforming the polygons to a projected coordinate system (Massachusetts State Plane), but then immediately transforming the points back to WGS84 lat/lon coordinates (4326) so that it will display on the leaflet map correctly.

MA_state_plane <- "+proj=lcc +lat_1=41.71666666666667 +lat_2=42.68333333333333 +lat_0=41 +lon_0=-71.5 +x_0=200000 +y_0=750000 +ellps=GRS80 +units=m +no_defs "

WGS84 <- "+proj=longlat +ellps=WGS84 +datum=WGS84 +no_defs"

nhood_points <- st_centroid(
  st_transform(cambridge_nhoods, crs = MA_state_plane)) %>%
  st_transform(WGS84)

leaflet(nhood_points) %>%
  addProviderTiles(providers$Stamen.TonerLite) %>%
  addCircles(label = ~label,
             fillColor = ~pal(case_rate),
             stroke = FALSE, 
             radius = 50, 
             fillOpacity = 1) %>% 
  addLegend(pal = pal, 
            values = ~case_rate,
            bins = 3,
            opacity = 0.7, title = "Cases per 10,000 residents",
            position = "topright")

Interpolation

Now, we can use raster interpolation to make a guess (and interpolation is just fancy guessing) about whats happening between those points.

The raster functions, including for spatial interpolation, work with an older data format (Spatial* - or sp) that what weve been working with (Simple Features - or sf). Thats fine because its pretty easy to convert back and forth. While Im at it, Im going to convert my points and polygons to state plane coordinates (so that the distance measurements used in the raster interpolation will be accurate).

nhood_pts_sp <- nhood_points %>%
  st_transform(MA_state_plane) %>%
  as_Spatial()

nhood_poly_sp <- cambridge_nhoods %>%
  st_transform(MA_state_plane) %>%
  as_Spatial()

Now, we need to create an empty raster that covers the area of Cambridge (the extent of the neighborhoods polygon) with a resolution of 10 meters (each cell represents 10 meters).

cambridge_raster <- raster(nhood_poly_sp, res=10)

Now Ill create a raster showing the variation in COVID rates using the inverse-distance weighting method. The first two lines below do the raster interpolation. The next line clips the raster layer to the extents of the neighborhood

gs <- gstat(formula=case_rate~1, locations=nhood_pts_sp)
idw_interp <- interpolate(cambridge_raster, gs)

idw_interp_clip <- mask(idw_interp, nhood_poly_sp)

Now we can show this raster layer on a map.

leaflet(nhood_points) %>%
  addProviderTiles(providers$Stamen.TonerLite) %>%
  addRasterImage(idw_interp_clip, colors = pal, opacity = 0.8) %>% 
  addLegend(pal = pal, 
            values = ~case_rate,
            bins = 3,
            opacity = 0.7, title = "Estimated cases per<br>10,000 residents",
            position = "topright")
